# Component Architecture Standards

## Core Rules

1. **Pure presentational** — components accept props, return JSX, no data fetching
2. **Under 200 lines** — split into smaller components if larger
3. **Always define a TypeScript prop interface** — no implicit props, no `any`
4. **Never import from `lib/data/`** — data flows in via props only
5. **Feature-based folders** — group related components together

## Folder Structure

```
components/
├── hero/
│   ├── HeroSection.tsx
│   └── HeroBackground.tsx
├── service-detail/
│   ├── ServiceDetail.tsx
│   └── ServiceCard.tsx
├── seo/
│   └── JsonLd.tsx
└── ui/
    ├── Button.tsx
    └── SectionHeading.tsx
```

## Component Template

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — typed props, semantic HTML, no data imports, mobile-first
interface ServiceCardProps {
  title: string
  description: string
  icon: string
  href: string
}

export function ServiceCard({ title, description, icon, href }: ServiceCardProps) {
  return (
    <article className="flex flex-col gap-3 p-6 md:p-8">
      <span aria-hidden="true">{icon}</span>
      <h3 className="text-lg font-semibold">{title}</h3>
      <p className="text-sm text-neutral-600">{description}</p>
      <a href={href} aria-label={`Learn more about ${title}`}>Learn more</a>
    </article>
  )
}

// ❌ BAD — fetches data, no interface, hardcoded content
export function ServiceCard() {
  const data = require('@/lib/data/services') // NEVER
  return <div>Our Services</div>              // hardcoded
}
```

## Client Components

Only use `"use client"` when the component needs:
- `useState` / `useEffect` / `useReducer`
- Event handlers with complex state
- Browser APIs
- Animation libraries (Framer Motion etc.)

Forms always need `"use client"`.

## HTML Semantics

Use semantic elements: `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`.
Every interactive element needs an `aria-label` if the text label alone is ambiguous.
